e, Cornwall, England":"Whitstone, Cornwall, Engleska, United Kingdom","Whitby, Yorkshire, England":"Whitby, Yorkshire, England"},"cs":{"1281–":"1281–Zesnulý","1281–Male":"1281–Zesnulý","1266–1316":"1266–1316","1312–1380":"1312–1380","1312–1412":"1312–1412","1250–1291":"1250–1291","1254–1284":"1254–1284","1284":"1284","1382":"1382","1250":"1250","1281":"1281","1380":"1380","1280":"1280","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1316":"1316","1315":"1315","1412":"1412","1312":"1312","1266":"1266","1254":"1254","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Whitstone, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Whitstone, Cornwall, Anglie, United Kingdom","Whitstone,Cornwall,England":"Whitstone, Cornwall, Anglie, United Kingdom","Whitstone, Cornwall, England":"Whitstone, Cornwall, Anglie, United Kingdom","Whitby, Yorkshire, England":"Whitby, Yorkshire, Anglie"},"da":{"1281–":"1281–Afdød","1281–Male":"1281–Afdød","1266–1316":"1266–1316","1312–1380":"1312–1380","1312–1412":"1312–1412","1250–1291":"1250–1291","1254–1284":"1254–1284","1284":"1284","1382":"1382","1250":"1250","1281":"1281","1380":"1380","1280":"1280","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1316":"1316","1315":"1315","1412":"1412","1312":"1312","1266":"1266","1254":"1254","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Whitstone, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Whitstone, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Whitstone,Cornwall,England":"Whitstone, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Whitstone, Cornwall, England":"Whitstone, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Whitby, Yorkshire, England":"Whitby, Jórvík, England"},"nl":{"1281–":"1281–Overleden","1281–Male":"1281–Overleden","1266–1316":"1266–1316","1312–1380":"1312–1380","1312–1412":"1312–1412","1250–1291":"1250–1291","1254–1284":"1254–1284","1284":"1284","1382":"1382","1250":"1250","1281":"1281","1380":"1380","1280":"1280","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1316":"1316","1315":"1315","1412":"1412","1312":"1312","1266":"1266","1254":"1254","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Whitstone, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Whitstone, Cornwall, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Whitstone,Cornwall,England":"Whitstone, Cornwall, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Whitstone, Cornwall, England":"Whitstone, Cornwall, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Whitby, Yorkshire, England":"Whitby, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"1281–":"1281–Deceased","1281–Male":"1281–Deceased","1266–1316":"1266–1316","1312–1380":"1312–1380","1312–1412":"1312–1412","1250–1291":"1250–1291","1254–1284":"1254–1284","1284":"1284","1382":"1382","1250":"1250","1281":"1281","1380":"1380","1280":"1280","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1316":"1316","1315":"1315","1412":"1412","1312":"1312","1266":"1266","1254":"1254","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Whitstone, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Whitstone, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Whitstone,Cornwall,England":"Whitstone, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Whitstone, Cornwall, England":"Whitstone, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Whitby, Yorkshire, England":"Whitby, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Goode","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Midlands): variant of   Good  . This name has been used in Ireland since the 16th century.","Possibly an Americanized form of Dutch   Goede  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Good","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>gode</i> ‘good’ (Old English <i>gōd</i>).","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Gode</i>, representing either Old English <i>Goda</i> (male) or <i>Gode</i> (female), in part a byname and in part a short form of various compound names with the first element <i>gōd</i>, or perhaps a pet form of Old French names in <i>God-</i> such as   Godfrey  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of German   Gut   and   Guth  , or Dutch <b>Goed</b> and   Goede  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":9,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":34,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":47,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":101,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Goode was born in 1281, in Whitstone, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom, his father, Richard Goode, was 31 and his mother, Mrs Goode, was 27. He had at least 1 son with Mrs Richard Goode. He died in Whitby, Yorkshire, England."},"et":{"1281–":"1281–Surnud","1281–Male":"1281–Surnud","1266–1316":"1266–1316","1312–1380":"1312–1380","1312–1412":"1312–1412","1250–1291":"1250–1291","1254–1284":"1254–1284","1284":"1284","1382":"1382","1250":"1250","1281":"1281","1380":"1380","1280":"1280","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1316":"1316","1315":"1315","1412":"1412","1312":"1312","1266":"1266","1254":"1254","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Whitstone, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Whitstone, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Whitstone,Cornwall,England":"Whitstone, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Whitstone, Cornwall, England":"Whitstone, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Whitby, Yorkshire, England":"Whitby, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1281–":"1281–Kuollut","1281–Male":"1281–Kuollut","1266–1316":"1266–1316","1312–1380":"1312–1380","1312–1412":"1312–1412","1250–1291":"1250–1291","1254–1284":"1254–1284","1284":"1284","1382":"1382","1250":"1250","1281":"1281","